<section label="getting-familiar-with-systems"><title> Getting Familiar with Systems </title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			When we first learned about differential equations, we focused on single equations with one dependent variable. But what if we have multiple dependent variables? How do we handle systems of equations where each variable evolves over time?
		</p>

		<p>
			Many systems of differential equations can be understood as a collection of independent first-order equations. In this section, we will explore the foundations of systems of equations, starting with uncoupled systems and moving on to coupled systems. We will also introduce the concept of a phase plane, which is a tool for visualizing the behavior of systems.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection label="what-are-systems"><title> What are Systems </title>

		<p>
			Recall that a solution to a differential equation is a function that <xref ref="par-what-is-a-solution-satisfies-a-de" text="custom">statisfies</xref> the equation. Up to now, there was always one equation  we talk about systems of differential equations, we mean a set of equations that describe how multiple dependent variables change over time. Each variable can depend on one or more independent variables, and they can interact with each other in various ways.
		</p>

		<p>
			For example, consider a system with two dependent variables, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. We might have equations like:
		</p>
		<md>
			<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} = f(x, y) </mrow>
			<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = g(x, y) </mrow>
		</md>
		<p>
			In this case, <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are functions that describe how <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> change over time, potentially depending on each other.
		</p>
		<p>
			We can also have systems with more than two variables, like <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m>. The equations might look like:
		</p>
		<md>
			<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} = f(x, y, z) </mrow>
			<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = g(x, y, z) </mrow>
			<mrow> \frac{dz}{dt} = h(x, y, z) </mrow>
		</md>
		<p>
			In this case, <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, and <m>h</m> are functions that describe how each variable changes over time, potentially depending on all the other variables.
		</p>
		<p>
			Understanding systems of differential equations is crucial because many real-world phenomena involve multiple interacting variables. For example, in ecology, we might model the populations of predators and prey, where the growth of one population depends on the other. In physics, we might model the motion of multiple objects that influence each other's trajectories.
		</p>
		<p>
			In the next sections, we will explore how to solve these systems, starting with uncoupled systems and moving on to partially coupled and fully coupled systems. We will also introduce visualization tools like phase planes to help us understand the behavior of these systems.
		</p>

		<paragraphs><title> How are they the Same </title>
			<p>
				At their core, systems of differential equations are just collections of first-order equations. Each equation describes how one dependent variable changes over time, potentially depending on other variables in the system.
			</p>
			<p>
				For example, in a system with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we might have:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} = f(x, y) </mrow>
				<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} = g(x, y) </mrow>
			</md>
			<p>
				This is similar to a single first-order differential equation, but now we have two equations that can interact with each other.
			</p>
			<p>
				The key difference is that in a system, we have multiple dependent variables that can influence each other. This adds complexity but also allows us to model more realistic scenarios where multiple factors are at play.
			</p>
			<p>
				Just like with single equations, we can use techniques like separation of variables, integrating factors, and substitution to solve systems of differential equations. The solutions will give us functions that describe how each variable evolves over time.
			</p>
			<p>
				Overall, systems of differential equations are a natural extension of the concepts we've already learned. They allow us to model more complex interactions and behaviors, making them a powerful tool in mathematics and science.
			</p>
			
		</paragraphs>

		<paragraphs><title> How are they Different </title>

			<p>
				The main difference between systems of differential equations and single equations is the presence of multiple dependent variables that can interact with each other. In a single equation, we have one dependent variable that evolves over time based on its own rate of change. In a system, we have multiple dependent variables, each with its own rate of change, which can depend on the other variables in the system.
			</p>
			<p>
				This interaction can lead to more complex behaviors, such as oscillations, stability, and chaos, which are not present in single equations. For example, in a predator-prey model, the population of predators depends on the population of prey, and vice versa. This creates a dynamic relationship that can lead to oscillations in both populations over time.
			</p>
			<p>
				Solving systems of differential equations often requires different techniques than solving single equations. We may need to use matrix methods, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors to analyze the stability and behavior of the system as a whole.
			</p>
			<p>
				In summary, systems of differential equations allow us to model more complex interactions between multiple dependent variables, leading to richer behaviors and requiring different solution techniques compared to single equations.
			</p>
			
		</paragraphs>

