		<subsection label="partially-coupled-systems"><title> Two Quantities - One-way Interaction </title>
			<p>
				In the previous example, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> changed independently. But what happens if one variable begins to influence the other? Let's explore a system where <m>x</m> evolves on its own, but <m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>:
			</p>

			<md>
				<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt}	\amp = -x		\amp \text{with} \quad x(0) = 1 </mrow>
				<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt}	\amp = -2y + x	\amp \text{with} \quad y(0) = 0 </mrow>
			</md>

			<p>
				This system describes how <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> change over time. <m>x</m> follows a simple decay, while <m>y</m> responds to the current value of <m>x</m>. We can think of <m>x</m> as a driving force and <m>y</m> as the response.
			</p>

			<p>
				The first equation is familiarâ€”it's just exponential decay. We can solve it right away:
			</p>

			<me>
				x(t) = e^{-t}
			</me>

			<p>
				Once we know <m>x(t)</m>, the second equation becomes:
			</p>

			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dt} = -2y + e^{-t}
			</me>

			<p>
				This is a first-order linear equation, which we can solve using an integrating factor.
			</p>

			<p>
				This is called a <em>partially coupled</em> system: <m>x</m> evolves on its own, while <m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>. It's a one-way interactionâ€”<m>x</m> affects <m>y</m>, but not the other way around.
			</p>

			<exercise label="chkpt-building-up-to-systems-1-2-1"><title> Partial Coupling is One-Way </title>
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						In a partially coupled system, one variable affects the other, but not vice versa.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Exactly. In these systems, one equation is independent and can be solved first. The second equation depends on the first.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</exercise>

			<p>
				This situation can model real-world problems where one process drives another. For example, suppose <m>x(t)</m> represents the light entering a greenhouse, and <m>y(t)</m> models plant growth. The light level doesn't depend on the plant, but the plant's growth rate depends on both its current state <m>y</m> and the incoming light <m>x</m>.
			</p>

			<example xml:id="ex-partial-coupling"><title> A Partially Coupled System </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Solve the partially coupled system:
					</p>
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt}	\amp = -x		\amp \text{with} \quad x(0) = 1 </mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt}	\amp = -2y + x	\amp \text{with} \quad y(0) = 0 </mrow>
					</md>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						This system is partially coupled: the equation for <m>x</m> is independent, while <m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>. We'll solve it in two steps.
					</p>

					<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Solve the equation for <m>x</m>. This is exponential decay:</p>

					<me>
						\frac{dx}{dt} = -x \quad \Rightarrow \quad x(t) = e^{-t}
					</me>

					<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Substitute <m>x(t)</m> into the equation for <m>y</m>:</p>

					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dt} = -2y + e^{-t}
					</me>

					<p>
						This is a linear equation. We'll solve it using an integrating factor. First, write it in standard form:
					</p>

					<me>
						y' + 2y = e^{-t}, \quad \mu(t) = e^{2t}
					</me>

					<p>
						Multiply both sides by the integrating factor:
					</p>

					<me>
						e^{2t} \cdot \frac{dy}{dt} + 2e^{2t} y = e^{t}
					</me>

					<p>
						The left-hand side is the derivative of <m>e^{2t} y</m>:
					</p>

					<me>
						\frac{d}{dt} \left( e^{2t} y \right) = e^t
					</me>

					<p>
						Integrate both sides:
					</p>

					<me>
						e^{2t} y = \int e^t\, dt = e^t + C
					</me>

					<p>
						Solve for <m>y(t)</m>:
					</p>

					<me>
						y(t) = e^{-t} + C e^{-2t}
					</me>

					<p>
						Use the initial condition <m>y(0) = 0</m>:
					</p>

					<me>
						0 = 1 + C \quad \Rightarrow \quad C = -1
					</me>

					<p>
						So the full solution is:
					</p>

					<me>
						\begin{aligned}
						x(t) \amp = e^{-t} \\
						y(t) \amp = e^{-t} - e^{-2t}
						\end{aligned}
					</me>

					<p>
						The function <m>x(t)</m> decays smoothly, while <m>y(t)</m> is temporarily lifted by <m>x(t)</m> before decaying to zero. This kind of response is typical in systems where one variable drives the other without feedback.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<conclusion><title> ðŸ“¤ Wrap-Up </title>

				<paragraphs><title> Summary </title>
					<p>
						<ul>
							<li>In a partially coupled system, one equation is independent, and the other depends on it.</li>
							<li>
								<p>
									To solve a partially coupled system:
									<ul>
										<li>Solve the independent equation first.</li>
										<li>Then substitute into the second equation and solve it.</li>
									</ul>
								</p>
							</li>
							<li>These systems model one-way interactions where one quantity influences another, but not vice versa.</li>
						</ul>
					</p>
				</paragraphs>

				<paragraphs><title> Reading Questions </title>
					<exercise><title> Answer the Following </title>
